{{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Apple Feast of the Saviour |type = ethnic |image = Apples on tree 2011 G1.jpg |imagesize = |caption = Apples |official_name = |nickname = |observedby = |litcolor = |longtype = |significance = |begins = |ends = |date = August 19 |scheduling = same day each year |duration = 1 day |frequency = annual |celebrations = |observances = |relatedto = }} The '''Apple Feast of the Saviour'''<ref>http://mcdiocese.com/en/619-avgusta-%E2%80%93-svyatoe-preobrazhenie-gospoda-boga-i-spasa-nashego-iisusa-xrista%E2%80%A6-vtoroj-yablochnyj-spas/</ref> (sometimes the '''Feast of the Saviour on the Hill''')<ref>{{cite book | last = Ivanits | first = Linda | title = Russian folk belief | publisher = M.E. Sharpe | year = 1992 | page = 24 | isbn = 0873328892 }}</ref> is an [[East Slavs|Eastern Slavic]] folk name for the [[Feast of the Transfiguration]], which is observed on August 19.
It is the second of the three Feasts of the Saviour. The others are the ''Honey Feast of the Saviour'', which is celebrated on August 14 (or August 1, Julian Calendar) and the ''Nut Feast of the Saviour'', which is celebrated on August 29 (or August 16, Julian Calendar).
The holiday has a pre-Christian origin and is associated with harvesting of ripe fruits, especially apples. In the Byzantine Empire there was tradition to bless harvested grapes during the Feast of Transfiguration. In Russia, apples are more common than grapes, hence the name of the feast. There are processions and blessings of harvests. Usually, on that day, people from [[Russia]], [[Ukraine]] and [[Belarus]] eat apples, apple pies, or other dishes containing apples, even if they are not Orthodox Christians.<gallery> File:Feast of Transfiguration in Spas village 06.jpg| File:Feast of Transfiguration in Spas village 08.jpg| File:Feast of Transfiguration in Spas village 13.jpg| File:Feast of Transfiguration in Spas village 21.jpg| File:Feast of Transfiguration in Sopiv, Ukraine 06.jpg| File:Feast of Transfiguration in Sopiv, Ukraine 09.jpg| </gallery>
