The '''Cold Springs Fire''' started July 12, 2008, eleven miles north of [[Trout Lake, Washington|Trout Lake]] in Washington.  It was contained and put out in August 2008.

The fire was started by lightning on July 12 and spread rapidly through heavy dead timber, eventually burning a total of 7,993 acres before full containment was reached on August 1. Of the area burned, 4,723 acres were in the [[Gifford Pinchot National Forest]], 1,623 on the [[Yakama Indian Reservation]], 1,076 on land managed by the [[Washington Department of Natural Resources]], and 307 on privately owned lands. At the peak of firefighting efforts, over 1,000 personnel were assigned to combat the blaze. In total, 1,037 firefighters from 33 units were needed to reach containment.<ref name=USDA>{{cite web|title=INCIWEB – Cold Spring Fire|url=https://fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/fsbdev3_005731.pdf|website=USDA|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>

The fire neared [[Mount Adams (Washington)|Mount Adams]] as it spread north of [[Trout Lake, Washington|Trout Lake]] causing closings for several trails and camp grounds.<ref name=Andrew>{{cite web|last1=Engelson|first1=Andrew|title=Fire Closes Trails Near Mount Adams, the state's highest peak |url=http://www.wta.org/signpost/fire-closes-trails-near-mount-adams|website=Washington Trails Association|publisher=Washington Trails Association|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>  Fire officials said it was the largest fire the area had received in decades, and the dangerous fire conditions allowed it to grow and spread quickly through dead trees and winds up to 25&nbsp;mph.  However, people were expecting a large fire and had been preparing so that no homes or people were threatened in the event.<ref name=Jung>{{cite web|last1=Tomlinson|first1=Stuart|last2=Jung|first2=Helen|title=Mt. Adams fire biggest in decades in Washington's south Cascades|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/environment/index.ssf/2008/07/mount_adams_fire_moving_fast.html|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>  Although no structures were burned, a 1909 historic guard station had to be wrapped in fire-retardant material.<ref name=Jung />

